{{For|the medical sociology concept|Overcrowding}} [[File:CrowdingDemo.gif|right|frame|A demonstration of the crowding effect. Fixate on the "x" and attempt to identify the central (or single) letter appearing to the right. The presence of flankers should make the task more difficult.]] '''Crowding''' is a [[perception|perceptual]] phenomenon where the [[Cognitive neuroscience of visual object recognition|recognition of objects]] (or graphemes) presented away from the [[Fovea centralis|fovea]] is impaired by the presence of other neighbouring objects (sometimes called "flankers").<ref name=Levi>{{cite journal |author=Levi D |title=Crowding - an essential bottleneck for object recognition: a mini-review |journal=Vision Research |volume=48 |issue=5 |pages=635–654 |date=February 2008 |doi=10.1016/j.visres.2007.12.009 |pmid=18226828 |pmc=2268888}}</ref> It has been suggested that crowding occurs due to mandatory integration of the crowded objects by a [[Pattern recognition|texture-processing neural mechanism]].<ref name=ParkesEtAl>{{cite journal |author1=Parkes L |author2=Lund J |author3=Angelucci A |author4=Solomon JA |author5=Morgan M |title=Compulsory averaging of crowded orientation signals in human vision |journal=Nature Neuroscience |volume=4 |issue=7 |pages=739–744 |year=2001 |doi=10.1038/89532}}</ref>
Crowding deficits have been specifically found in neuropsychiatric disorders such as schizophrenia and autism and may have profound clinical implications in these disorders.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kraehenmann|first=Rainer|author2=Vollenweider FX |author3=Seifritz E |author4=Kometer M |title=Crowding deficits in the visual periphery of schizophrenia patients|journal=PLOS ONE|year=2012|volume=7|issue=9|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0045884|url=http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0045884 |pmid=23049884 |pages=e45884 |pmc=3458825}}</ref>
If objects remain within your visual field over time, then [[priming (psychology)]] begins to occur and the objects become less cluttered.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Kristjánsson | first1 = A. | last2 = Heimisson | first2 = P. | last3 = Róbertsson | first3 = G. | last4 = Whitney | first4 = D. | year = 2013 | title = Attentional priming releases crowding | url = | journal = Attention, Perception, & Psychophysics | volume = 75 | issue = 7| pages = 1323–1329 | doi=10.3758/s13414-013-0558-2}}</ref>
