{{infobox organization/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL|onlysourced=yes|logo=Japanese Medical Marijuana Association logo.gif}} The '''Japanese Medical Marijuana Association''' ({{lang-ja|医療大麻を考える会}}, ''Iryō taima o kangaeru kai'') was founded in 1999 and seeks to improve access to [[medical cannabis]]. Its status under Japanese law is Specified Nonprofit Corporation (特定非営利活動法人).<ref>{{citation|title=アピール|trans-title=Appeal|publisher=Japanese Medical Marijuana Association|url=http://iryotaima.net/wp/?page_id=59|accessdate=2018-04-17}}</ref>{{secondary source needed|date=April 2018}} Due to the illegality of cannabis in Japan, the organization has investigated leveraging legal medical [[cannabis in Guam]] for Japanese patients.
In 2014, JMMA president Koichi Maeda met with Guamanian senator Tina Muña-Barnes regarding Guam's medical cannabis program. In 2017, Maeda returned and met with governor [[Eddie Calvo]]. Maeda's intent was to develop Guam as a destination for Japanese people seeking cannabis remedies, and for the JMMA to promote cannabis [[medical tourism]] to Guam.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.postguam.com/news/local/medical-marijuana-advocate-seeks-involvement-for-non-residents/article_6d5bef2c-e83b-11e6-a736-332d27c83ee6.html |title= Medical marijuana advocate seeks involvement for non-residents |author= John Connor, ''Post News'' |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{citation|newspaper=[[Pacific Daily News]]|location=Hagåtña, Guam|title=Group eyes medical pot tourism|author=Jerick Sablan|date=February 4, 2017|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/2017/02/04/group-eyes-medical-pot-tourism/97432546/}}</ref>
Japan's strict laws prevent Japanese citizens from using cannabis even when outside of Japan. However, Maeda stated that Japanese citizens with incurable diseases would be exempt from this law.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.postguam.com/news/local/gvb-to-research-tourism-related-medical-marijuana/article_47be4362-eb67-11e6-955e-07acd74cc1b7.html |title= GVB to research tourism-related medical marijuana |author= Tihu Lujan, ''Post News'' |publisher=}}</ref>
