{{Infobox food | name = Macroom Oatmeal | image = Macroom oatmeal porridge, topped with muscovado sugar and butter.jpg | caption = Macroom oatmeal porridge, topped with muscovado sugar and butter | alternate_name = | country = Ireland | region = | national_cuisine = Irish | creator = <!-- or | creators = --> | year = | mintime = | maxtime = | type = | course = Breakfast | served = Hot | main_ingredient = Stone-ground oats | minor_ingredient = | variations = | serving_size = 100 g | calories = | protein = | fat = | carbohydrate = | glycemic_index = | similar_dish = | other = | complexity = }}
'''Macroom Oatmeal''' is a traditional stone-ground Irish oatmeal produced in [[Macroom]], County Cork, Ireland, at Walton's Mill, the last surviving stone mill in Ireland.<ref name="weinzweig">{{cite web|last=Weinzweig|first=Ari|title=Ireland's Renowned Oatmeal|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2009/06/irelands-renowned-oatmeal/19101/|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> It was taken aboard [[Slow Food]]'s [[Ark of Taste]] in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|title=Macroom Irish Oatmeal|url=http://www.slowfoodfoundation.com/ark/details/1246/stone-ground-irish-oatmeal#.UzrVqceQMpQ|publisher=Slow Food|accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> one of only seven Irish foods ever selected for the ark.
==History== The mill has been operated continuously by the same family since the 1700s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grant|first=Steve|title=Sowing Your Wild Oats: Comparing Macroom Oatmeal To Quaker Oats Is Like Comparing Caviar To Hamburgers|url=http://articles.courant.com/2006-03-05/features/0603030707_1_oatmeal-stoneware-bowls|work=The Hartford Courant|accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> Donal Creedon, great-great-great-great-grandson of founder Richard Walton, now operates the mill. [[Michelin star]]-winning chef [[Myrtle Allen]] developed the Macroom Biscuit recipe<ref>{{cite web|last=Hix|first=Mark|title=Macroom Oatmeal Biscuits|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/recipes/macroom-oatmeal-biscuits-523520.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> which appears on the package.
==Production method== Macroom oatmeal is stone-ground, then kiln-toasted.<ref name=andrews />
==Reception== [[Saveur Magazine]] called it "different from anyone else's in Ireland, full of flavor when simply cooked and immensely satisfying in its grainy texture."<ref>{{cite web|last=Andrews|first=Colman|title=County Cork: Food Capital|url=http://www.saveur.com/article/Travels/County-Cork-Food-Capital|work=Saveur|accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> Food writer [[John Thorne (writer)|John Thorne]] said it "may well be the best oatmeal I've ever eaten."<ref>{{cite web|title=The Original Macroom Oatmeal|url=http://www.cookingisfun.biz/shop/food/the-original-macroom-oatmeal.html|publisher=Ballymaloe Cookery School|accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> [[Fodor's]] Ireland mentions Macroom Oatmeal.<ref>{{cite book|title=Fodor's Ireland|date=2013|isbn=978-0876371244|page=350}}</ref> [[Darina Allen]] of [[Ballymaloe House]], where Macroom Oatmeal is served for breakfast, said that Macroom Oatmeal has "a cult following both at home and abroad."<ref>{{cite web|last=Allen|first=Darina|title=Wellbeck Abbey|url=http://letters.cookingisfun.ie/2011/04/30/welbeck-abbey/|publisher=Ballymaloe Cooking School|accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> [[James Beard Award|James Beard 2010 Cookbook of the Year]] ''The Country Cooking of Ireland'' says "(t)he best oatmeal for [[Stirabout]]...is Macroom, milled by Donal Creedon in the town of that name in County Cork."<ref name=andrews>{{cite book|last1=Andrews|first1=Colman|title=The Country Cooking of Ireland|date=12 December 2012|publisher=Chronicle Books|page=346|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKBdBblqiX0C&dq=donal+creedon+-meditation+-kagyu&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>
